## Founder Agreement & Equity

### Equity Split Considerations

Research shows several approaches ([Source](https://www.cakeequity.com/guides/founder-equity)):

| Split Type | Pros | Cons |
|------------|------|------|
| **50/50 Equal** | Signals true partnership, avoids conflict | May seem "immature" to investors, doesn't reflect different contributions |
| **60/40 or 55/45** | Reflects primary driver, clear tiebreaker | Potential resentment |
| **Dynamic/Milestone** | Fair based on actual contribution | Complex to administer |

#### Factors to Consider

| Factor | Travis | Trenton |
|--------|--------|---------|
| Original idea | ? | ? |
| Technical execution | **High** | Low |
| Business/operations | Medium | **High** |
| Capital contribution | ? | ? |
| Time commitment | ? | ? |
| Industry expertise (golf) | Medium | ? |
| Network/connections | ? | ? |

#### Recommended Approach

1. **Hold back 10-15% equity** for future allocation based on actual contributions
2. **Equal base split** (42.5% / 42.5%) with 15% reserve
3. **Vesting schedule** on all founder equity

### Vesting Schedule (Critical)

Standard founder vesting ([Source](https://terms.law/2023/07/18/navigating-founder-equity-and-vesting-schedules-a-guide-for-startup-founders/)):

```
4-Year Vesting with 1-Year Cliff

Year 0-1: 0% vested (cliff period)
Year 1:   25% vests immediately (passed cliff)
Year 2:   50% total vested (monthly 1/48)
Year 3:   75% total vested
Year 4:   100% fully vested
```

**Why vesting matters:**
- Protects if co-founder leaves early
- Shows commitment to investors
- Creates accountability
- Most investors **require** seeing vesting before funding

#### 83(b) Election

**Critical for US founders**: File IRS Form 83(b) within 30 days of stock grant to pay taxes on initial (low) value rather than at vesting when value may be higher ([Source](https://carta.com/learn/startups/equity-management/founder-shares/)).

### Operating Agreement Key Terms

A multi-member LLC operating agreement must include ([Source](https://www.legalgps.com/llc-operating-agreement/blog/the-ultimate-guide-to-multi-member-llc-operating-agreements)):

| Section | Key Decisions Needed |
|---------|---------------------|
| **Capital Contributions** | Initial investment amounts, non-cash contribution values |
| **Ownership %** | Percentage interest for each member |
| **Voting Rights** | Proportional vs per-capita, thresholds for major decisions |
| **Distributions** | When and how profits are distributed |
| **Management** | Member-managed vs manager-managed |
| **Decision Thresholds** | Majority vs supermajority vs unanimous requirements |
| **Transfer Restrictions** | Right of first refusal, approval requirements |
| **Dissolution** | Events that trigger dissolution, process |
| **Dispute Resolution** | Mediation, arbitration, buyout provisions |

#### Voting Thresholds Recommendation

| Decision Type | Threshold |
|---------------|-----------|
| Day-to-day operations | Either member |
| Hiring/firing employees | Majority |
| Expenditures >$5,000 | Majority |
| New ventures/subsidiaries | Unanimous |
| Taking on debt >$25,000 | Unanimous |
| Selling/transferring equity | Unanimous |
| Dissolution | Unanimous |
| Admitting new members | Unanimous |

